Descrease article font size
Increase article font size
EDMONTON – The last time Gavin Joseph Mandin was free, he was a 15-year-old boy with large round glasses, a child’s face, and acne-speckled skin.
Now he’s 36 and has spent more than half of his life in prison for the brutal and unexplained murders of his mother, stepfather and two sisters at the family home near Valleyview in August 1991.After 21 years in prison, Mandin was granted day parole by the National Parole Board on Oct. 31.Correctional Service of Canada and the National Parole Board would not comment on where Mandin will be living, or whether he has returned to Alberta. His parole reports come from the Ontario region.Mandin now goes by the name Gavin Ian Maclean, taking the name of his biological father as his middle and last names.									Story continues below advertisement
The murders happened on Aug. 6, 1991, moments after Mandin’s mother, Susan, 41, stepfather Maurice, 46, and sisters Islay, 12, and Janelle 10, pulled into the driveway of the family’s vacation home near Valleyview after a shopping trip. Inside the small three-room farmhouse, Mandin picked up a loaded .22-calibre rifle.“Some part of me took over,” he later said. “My dad got out of the car and I just kept shooting at him. I was enraged. I called my sister’s name and she looked at me and I didn’t have any conscious intent of doing anything, but the gun slung towards her and shot her.”
More on Canada
Company behind Instant Pot, founded in Canada, files for bankruptcy
Lost precious documents in the wildfires? IRCC will replace them for free
Telus delays Alberta fibre optic network, blames Ottawa’s Huawei ban
Canadians have right to healthy environment, new law says — but not right away
Mandin fired 10 times and killed all four people, shooting each of his sisters in the head from barely an inch away. He waited for his mother to look up at him before he killed her.The teen fired until he was out of bullets, and kept pulling the trigger even after the gun was empty.Afterward, Mandin got a knife and cut open his mother’s flowered blue dress, her bra and panties, leaving her body exposed. He tied his stepfather’s body to the back of an ATV and dragged it into some long summer grass, then drove the car with his mother and sisters’ bodies into the trees.Mandin stayed on the property for more than a day before packing up the family’s copper-coloured minivan with clothing, a cooler, two knives, a shotgun, and the rifle he’d used in the shootings. An avid reader and science fiction fan, he also took the Ray Bradbury mystery novel A Graveyard for Lunatics.									Story continues below advertisement
Police who tried to pull Mandin over were concerned only about his driving, and had no idea anyone had been hurt.Mandin was arrested after a high-speed chase, and later confessed the murders to police. He told officers he was planning to go home to St. Albert, and was then thinking of going up north “where nobody would have been able to find me.”The crime was shocking not only for its violence, but also for its senselessness. Mandin himself seemed unable to explain what he had done.“People keep coming up to me and saying, ‘why?’ I look back and think I was a pretty screwed-up kid … an egotistical power maniac,” he told the Journal in 1994. “It doesn’t make sense. At the time, the reasons seemed acceptable. Now I can’t even remember the reasons.”Mandin recalled being annoyed at having to do chores, feeling like a “slave,” and being put off by “the entire attitude of the household.”He told police after his arrest: “It was just anger building up over the years and the opportunity came up.”Those who knew the family also struggled to find an explanation. Mandin was a seemingly normal middle-class teenager, the child of two teachers, with a small but close circle of friends. He had an IQ of 133, in the “superior intelligence” range. He appeared to have a good relationship with his stepfather, Maurice, who had met and married Mandin’s mother about five years before the killings. Mandin’s biological parents divorced when he was a child.									Story continues below advertisement
“Nothing can explain this sudden turnaround that brought on this rage,” Mandin’s uncle Emile said in 1994.Mandin became a born-again Christian shortly after the murders, and was re-baptized while in custody at the Edmonton Young Offender Centre. He pleaded guilty to four counts of second-degree murder and was sentenced as an adult, receiving life in prison without parole for a minimum of 10 years.When Mandin first applied for parole in July 2001, the board declined his release – in large part because of his lack of remorse for the crime.“Remorse has always been a challenge for me,” Mandin told the board at the time.“I recognize how callous it sounds, but I remember the feeling of helplessness … feeling there was no way out.”Another parole report, generated when Mandin successfully applied for unescorted absences from prison in 2009, said he continued to “heap blame” on his mother for many years after the murders. But it also said Mandin had come to a greater understanding of his crime, realizing that he felt “a strong hostility” toward his mother from a very young age, and had started to blame her for all of the negative experiences in his life, while simultaneously craving her love, acceptance and attention.Psychological reports throughout the years have varied. Some early assessments found Mandin was a psychopath, but later reports and testing did not.
Trending Now
Family of B.C. man killed by toxic drugs donates $20M to treatment program
Donald Trump pleads not guilty to federal charges in classified docs case
Story continues below advertisement
A 2007 assessment found Mandin didn’t meet the criteria for such a diagnosis under the Hare Psychopathy Checklist, and a Violent Risk Appraisal Guide test found him a low risk to reoffend violently.The Parole Board decision said the most recent psychological report, prepared in August 2012, found Mandin was a good candidate for day parole because he had done well in prison and had complied with his correctional plan. The person preparing the report did notice “prominent narcissistic and obsessional features which could prove relatively maladaptive” within a community setting, the parole board said.Mandin’s risk for violent reoffence was found to be in the “low moderate” range.In its decision, the board told Mandin: “During your hearing you impressed as being candid and open about why you offended as you did and how you have come to terms with your actions.“You have not been able to rationally explain why you killed your sisters but it appears that you will never fully explain this action.”Mandin has had a few problems in prison and was once caught with contraband pornography and magazines about “a fictional vampire slayer,” but is described by the parole board as being an “exemplary” inmate. The parole reports say Mandin has completed numerous programs, and has worked, saved money, and participated actively in the Lifers’ Club and other inmate groups.									Story continues below advertisement
Under the conditions of his parole, Mandin is only allowed to have contact with one specific family member, who has been a support for him since the slayings.“The other members of the family have been severely traumatized by your actions and do not wish contact with you in any form whatsoever,” the most recent parole decision notes.Mandin must also take counselling, and report any relationships with women.“The act of cutting your mothers clothes after her murder is unexplained and appears in the context of inappropriate sexual fantasies,” the decision reads. “To ensure that any female is protected and is aware of your history, any such relationship must be reported forthwith.”Since he is serving a life sentence, Mandin will continue to be monitored in the community for the rest of his life, and could be re-incarcerated if his parole officer believes there are problems.Mandin’s family declined to be interviewed about his release, but a 2011 parole board report described them as being profoundly devastated.At his first parole hearing in 2001, Mandin’s older stepsister, Monique, said she was afraid of Mandin and dreaded his release from prison.“Honestly, it’s something I’m not even capable of imagining,” she said at that time. “I can’t imagine what my life will be like when he’s released.”									Story continues below advertisement
She described the family’s horror as “asphyxiating.”Sitting down with a Journal reporter after his sentencing hearing in January 1994, Mandin said he wanted to take programs for his anger, to learn to empathize with other people, and “to correct some things that I know are a little crooked in my brain.”Mandin said then the rest of his family didn’t need to be afraid of him, and that he looked ahead to the time of his release, which 19 years later has finally arrived.“When I get out, I’d be content to find a little house somewhere,” he said. “Get married, and live whatever life God wants me to.”
