INSERT INTO news_stories (id, record_id, url, body_text, ai_summary) VALUES ('e2d7f4f1-1e60-42ff-a437-72700e1237fe', '25423d5f-8e5c-4b28-9c63-96de075c0e8b', 'https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/man-denied-parole-10-years-after-killing-family/article4150798/', 'Skip to main contentAdChoicesCanadaWorldBusinessInvestingWatchlistPersonal FinanceOpinionPoliticsSportsLifeArtsDriveReal EstatePodcastsMan denied parole 10 years after killing familyJill MahoneyEdmontonPublished July 19, 2001This article was published more than 21 years ago. Some information may no longer be current.ShareA young Alberta man who murdered his family 10 years ago was denied parole yesterday.Gavin Mandin was 15 when he shot and killed his mother, stepfather and two sisters at their remote hobby farm near Valleyview, 300 kilometres northwest of Edmonton.Several members of his extended family attended yesterday&#39;s National Parole Board hearing, held at the Bowden Institution, a medium-security jail south of Red Deer. A few read prepared statements opposing his release.In addressing the three-member panel, Mr. Mandin acknowledged he had little chance of being granted parole. He also talked at some length about the rage he felt toward his mother.&#34;At the time I thought I was perfectly justified in what I did,&#34; he said. &#34;I still see myself as a victim.&#34;Mr. Mandin&#39;s aunt, Colette Mandin-Kosowan, said earlier this week she didn&#39;t think anyone in the family was ready for his release.&#34;Those 10 years have just gone by so quickly, it just seems unreal that we&#39;re already here when there&#39;s still grief issues to deal with,&#34; she said.Mr. Mandin told police he committed the Aug. 6, 1991 murders out of anger at having to do chores.In 1993, the teen pleaded guilty to second-degree murder in adult court, but was sentenced under the Young Offenders Act. He received the harshest possible penalty -- life with no parole eligibility for 10 years from the time of the crime.At the time of his guilty plea, his lawyer said he attacked his family as they drove into the yard. He shot his stepfather as he got out of the car and then shot his mother and sisters, 10-year-old Janelle and 12-year-old Islay, in the vehicle.Follow Jill Mahoney on Twitter: @jillsmahoneyOpens in a new windowReport an errorEditorial code of conductYour GlobeBuild your personal news feedMore infoFollow the author of this article:Jill MahoneyFollowYou must be logged in to follow.Log InCreate free accountCheck Following for new articlesTerms &amp; ConditionsCommunity GuidelinesPrivacy PolicyDisclaimerSkip footer navigationSubscribeDigital + Home DeliveryDigital AccessGlobe2GoThe New York TimesGlobe Email NewslettersGift SubscriptionBusiness servicesAdvertise with UsGroup SubscriptionsGlobe CampusContent LicensingDataStoreReport On Business Top 1000Globe Event CentreSophi.ioContact usAddress and Phone NumberPublic EditorStaffStaff PGP DirectorySecureDropSubmit an articleReader servicesMy globeandmail.com AccountTechnical Support &amp; FAQsManage my home deliveryManage my privacy preferencesManage my advertising preferencesMember BenefitsAbout usCompany informationWork at The GlobeAccessibilityEditorial Code of ConductSustainabilityLicensing &amp; PermissionsElection Advertising RegistrySubscribeDigital + Home DeliveryDigital AccessGlobe2GoThe New York TimesGlobe Email NewslettersGift SubscriptionBusiness servicesAdvertise with UsGroup SubscriptionsGlobe CampusContent LicensingDataStoreReport On Business Top 1000Globe Event CentreSophi.ioContact usAddress and Phone NumberPublic EditorStaffStaff PGP DirectorySecureDropSubmit an articleReader servicesMy globeandmail.com AccountTechnical Support &amp; FAQsManage my home deliveryManage my privacy preferencesManage my advertising preferencesMember BenefitsAbout usCompany informationWork at The GlobeAccessibilityEditorial Code of ConductSustainabilityLicensing &amp; PermissionsElection Advertising RegistryReturn to start of